title: For Sale:  CNC milled aluminum 80% lower AR receiver
postcontent:
These are milled out of a solid piece of aluminum block, not forged or cast in a mold.

These are some beautiful lower receivers, 80% complete to military specifications. These are NOT considered receivers yet by the ATF and are not serialized - meaning there's absolutely no tracking of these units and even if purchased through a gun shop, no background check is required and no paperwork filled out. 

 These are completely legal to own and complete into working receivers - 
 however, as will all things gun related, know the local, state, and federal laws that apply to your particular location and circumstances. You are responsible for You!

 All that is needed is a drill or drill press, some end mill bits (basically drill bits with flat ends) , and the jig; here's a few links to places selling the jigs:
 http://ar15jigs.com/drilljigs.html
 http://www.cncguns.com/tooling.html
 http://www.apex-brass.com/ut-arms-drill-jig-fixture.html

 Of all the places selling the jigs (and there are many more), I highly recommend CNCguns. Those guys have been there, done it (right) and now offer the proper pieces of equipment, videos, and first hand experience. Plus, their just plain nice guys and will take time out of their day to get on the phone and talk you through any problems.

 I ordered 5 of these when all h*ll broke loose earlier this year and I'll end up building out 3, that leaves 2 to sell. 

 Again, these are mill aluminum works of art that you can build into flawless operating guns that you'll be proud to own.

 I am able to accept payment via CC through Google Checkout (add 3.5%) and will only charge actual shipping (no "handling" fee), and these do not have to go through an FFL - they ship straight to your door.

title: For Sale:  Swedish Mauser M94/14  6.5x55
postcontent:
For sale is a sporterized Swedish Mauser M94/14 in the classic 6.5 x 55 caliber.  Interarms, long ago, imported a number of these hard to find classics.  To identify these carbines as "theirs", they scrubbed the year of manufacture commonly found on the breech and roll marked "Interarms G33/50".

The barrel is 18 inches long making this ideal for those of you who brush hunt deer, etc.  Add maneuverability to the legendary accuracy of the 6.5 x 55 cartridge and what's not to like.

The action rests in a sporterized Mauser stock as you can see from the photos.  The receiver has NOT been drilled or tapped, it's in its as original condition.  Magazine capacity is 5 rounds and this is one caliber that hasn't gone through the roof in terms of ammunition prices. 

The action, bolt, shroud, and safety are all matching numbers.  I've fired this rifle, it's accurate as all get out even with the iron sights and fun to shoot.

 I've got some taxes to pay and, if you have any familiarity with Swedish Mausers you'll see that the price is quite attractive as stated.  Not interested in any trades at this time.

Cash is king.  I live in the NW burbs of Milwaukee and will drive up to 30 minutes if you're a serious buyer.  Drop me an email with any questions and we'll go from there.  I have additional photos if you're interested.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Intratec AB-10 with 30-round Magazine
postcontent:
***Update: Firearm comes with 200-rounds of NIB 115 grain Winchester 9mm FMJ***

For sale is an Intratec AB-10 with a 30-round magazine.  

The AB-10 model was created when the Clinton administration banned TEC-9’s.  The “AB” reportedly stands for “Anti-Ban”; bless those folks at Intratec.  

If you’re looking for a highly accurate weapon with sub-MOA results - this ain’t it!  However, if you’re more of the “spray and pray” mindset then this is the tool for you.   

The AB-10 mechanicals are similar to those of the WW II era grease gun (which is still in limited use today by the US Army) but in 9mm.  It has a large bolt, a firing pin, two main springs, and that’s about it.  It’s simple and it’s reliable.  

This is a fun range weapon.  It’s not designed for surgical shooting.  It’s the kind of thing you pull out of the case, load, launch lead in a rapid downrange direction, and watch as folks gather around to take a peek and try it out.  

The firearm is only 10 ½” wide x 6 ¼“ high at the widest and tallest points without the magazine.  It takes up very little space and stores easily.  This makes it ideal for tucking into a bug-out bag, squirreling it away in a small lockbox, or even securing it in a vehicle.  

I am including the following with this sale: AB-10 firearm; 30-round magazine; 200-rounds of brass ammo (as listed above); and directions for assembling and disassembling the AB-10.  

I will need to see a PTP or conceal carry permit and valid ID.  I will fill out transfer paperwork for my records only, not to file anywhere else.  A copy of the transfer paperwork will be available for you as well. 

Although cash is king, I will trade this for a nice bolt action Savage with a decent scope in either .17HMR or .22LR.  If there is a difference in values we can work that out with additional trades or cash.  

Thanks for looking – see you on the zero line.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Nambu Type 94 8mm
postcontent:
Japanese Nambu Type 94 8mm pistol. The serial number is 55222,and it has the bakelite grips, which means it was probably made in late 1944. The gun is in great condition, with excellent bluing. Everything appears functional, though I haven't shot it. Comes with holster and two magazines. The holster is in rough condition, but there are very few Nambu 94s out there, let alone with holsters. $600 or best offer. 

Call or text Paul at REDACTED or email me through Armslist.  

The Nambu Type 94 pistol was adopted by the Imperial Japanese Army in 1934 (year 2594 of the contemporary Japanese calendar). It was developed to complement and eventually replace the older Type 14 Nambu pistol in military service, but limited industrial capabilities of the Imperial Japan didn't let it happen. Total production of these pistols between 1934 and 1945 is estimated at 65 - 70 thousands guns. Nambu Type 94 pistol is short recoil operated, locked breech weapon. The breech block (bolt) is made as a separate item and removable attached to the slide by a cross-bolt. The trigger is of single action type, with internal (concealed) hammer. Manual safety lever is located at the left side of the frame, above and to the rear of the grip panel. The single stack box magazine has capacity of just 6 rounds, magazine release button is located at the base of the trigger guard.
